When I was teaching school in San Antonio, I had a little girl in my name by the name of Eileen Balinski.
Smartest little thing that ever was.
And I didn't connect Balinski with anything being a Jew.
I knew where Belinsky's auction barn was out in the stockyards and everything, but it didn't.
We were having a Christmas program.
She said, Miss Ava, what kind of a program are we going to have for Christmas?
I said, well, Eileen, what would you like to have?
She says, let's have Christmas in all nations.
I said, well, us being sixth graders, that's what we're studying, every nation under the globe, so why not?
I said, that would be fine with me.
She said, can I have Israel?
And one little boy come running up to me, and he said, can I have Austria?
And, you know, just one right after the other came and asked if they could have these and this and that.
I had one little Mexican boy, and he wanted Mexico.
But I said, now I want your children to be sure and ask your parents if this is all right when you start out.
Because let me tell you, when we start this program, there is no two options.
nations in the world that celebrate Christmas at Christmas time, like the Americans do.
Well, their eyes got big as dollars.
And I said, now, not everybody celebrates Christmas as December the 26th.
And I said, you're going to have to tell them why.
You celebrate Christmas at a certain time.
And you'll be dressed in your costumes, and you'll tell of your foods, and you'll tell of your customs.
Well, that just tickled them to death, but they all thought it would be December the 26th, 25th.
